A '''quasi-corporation''' is<ref>https://stats.oecd.org/glossary/detail.asp?ID=2225</ref> an entity that exercises some of the functions of a [[company (law)|corporation]], but has not been granted [[Juristic person|separate legal personality]] by [[statute]]. For example, a public corporation with limited authority and powers such as a county or school district is a quasi-corporation. In the [[United States]], such entities are often referred to as ''quasi-municipal corporations''.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}
A quasi corporation is a business which has operated as a corporation without completing the legal requirements, often in the period just before formal incorporation. It is a corporation formed with good faith intent but lacking a formality.
It is also a corporation consisting of a person or body of persons invested with some of the qualities of an artificial person, though not expressly incorporated, esp. the official of certain municipal divisions such as counties, schools districts, and the towns of some states of the United States, certain church officials, as a churchwarden, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://definitions.uslegal.com/q/quasi-corporation/|title=Quasi Corporation Law and Legal Definition {{!}} USLegal, Inc.|last=Inc.|first=US Legal,|website=definitions.uslegal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref>
Some examples of quasi public corporations include the following:
* Sallie Mae * Fannie Mae * Communications Satellite Corporation (“COMSAT”) * U.S. Postal Service <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upcounsel.com/quasi-public-corporation|title=Quasi Public Corporation: Everything You Need to Know|website=UpCounsel|language=en|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref>
